Prior to selecting or designing the content of a control condition, researchers first need to identify the most appropriate study design. The two most common designs, historically, are waitlist control and treatment as usual or usual care. Though a waitlist control design is convenient and may address ethical concerns related to providing no intervention, it is still considered a weak design because it is not concurrent with the active intervention  (5) . Specific to nutrition and weight-loss interventions, two systematic reviews found that roughly onethird to one-half of studies had no control or an inactive control condition (including waitlist control)  (6, 7) . The other most common control condition, considered to be a passive control condition, is usual care (5-7). However, usual care is often a nebulous concept with few studies providing an adequate description of what is involved  (6, 7) . In a review of weight-loss studies, usual care made up 44% of control conditions and, when described, typically involved dissemination of print materials about healthy behaviours or, less frequently, brief education sessions to promote healthy behaviours  (7) .

The strongest design includes an active control condition to account for the nature and frequency of attention participants receive in behavioural interventions  (5) . These active control conditions should be concurrent, to account for any historical or maturation effects, and equivalent with regard to time, the extent of activities, and the nature of engagement (e.g., nature of activities, attention, support from staff)  (5, 6, 8) . The active control condition should also be equally attractive to participants; that is, though qualitatively different, it should be perceived to have equal value  (5, 6) . Providing an intervention of equal, if different, value also ensures that participants in the control condition are not wasting their time engaging in meaningless activities, addressing the ethical principles of respect for persons and justice  (5, 8) . Active control conditions should confer potential benefit to the participant, though that benefit should be independent of the primary study outcome (i.e., the benefit of the primary intervention being tested)  (8) . Following a comparative effectiveness research framework, Aycock and colleagues (2018) laid out nine essential considerations for behavioural intervention studies with active control conditions including: (1) the "active components" of the control intervention are not associated with the primary outcome of interest;

(2) there is no contamination between intervention groups; (3) the active control is comparable (as described above) to the primary intervention; (4) there is adequate and comparable training for both conditions; (5) the control condition is interesting and acceptable to the target population; (6) both interventions are evaluated, both with regard to fidelity and to study outcomes;  (7)  consideration is given to the resources required for intervention delivery and implementation; (8) the effects of both intervention conditions are quantifiable and measured;  (9)  consideration is given to ethical issues  (8) .
